cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM, cs.NE 

This paper is about using deep learning techniques to segment the optic disc and optic cup from fundus images, which is a computer vision problem. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a novel patch-based output space adversarial learning framework, which involves training a neural network to generate segmentation maps that are similar to the source domain. This involves techniques from machine learning and artificial intelligence, which makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also evaluates its framework on three public retinal fundus image datasets, which involves multimedia techniques, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper uses unsupervised domain adaptation to address the domain shift challenge, which involves techniques from neural networks and optimization, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category as well.
